WEBVTT

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:07.340
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.340 --> 00:00:08.940
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:10.590
You've been talking about
differentials.

00:00:10.590 --> 00:00:12.480
And one of the things that
you've shown is that some of

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:14.980
the stuff that we've been doing
with derivatives can

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:17.290
also be phrased in terms
of differentials.

00:00:17.290 --> 00:00:19.930
That for many purposes they
form a just a different

00:00:19.930 --> 00:00:21.980
language to compute
the same things.

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:24.660
So in particular one example
of that is linear

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:25.650
approximation.

00:00:25.650 --> 00:00:28.640
So I have a problem here that's
a linear approximation

00:00:28.640 --> 00:00:31.020
problem, but I'd like you to
do it using the method of

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:32.130
differentials.

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:34.700
So in particular I'd like
you to approximate the

00:00:34.700 --> 00:00:36.140
square root of 21.

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:38.630
And the way I'd like you to do
that is by using a linear

00:00:38.630 --> 00:00:42.110
approximation to the function f
of x equals the square root

00:00:42.110 --> 00:00:48.760
of 10x minus x squared based at
the point 2, x0 equals 2.

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:52.050
Note that, you know, why are
we using this function to

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:53.700
approximate square root of 21?

00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:57.540
Well because at 3, the function
value at 3, f of 3,

00:00:57.540 --> 00:01:00.020
is exactly equal to the
square root of 21.

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:04.230
So to approximate the square
root 21 means approximate the

00:01:04.230 --> 00:01:06.130
function value at 3.

00:01:06.130 --> 00:01:10.940
And so, you know, this function
has a nice value at x

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:15.030
equals 2, so we can use linear
approximation at 2 to try and

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:20.810
compute an approximation to the
function at x equals 3.

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:23.970
So why don't you take a couple
of minutes, work this out,

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:25.610
come back and we can work
it out together.

00:01:32.750 --> 00:01:34.020
All right, welcome back.

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:36.970
So we're doing linear
approximation here.

00:01:36.970 --> 00:01:38.290
And we're doing it with
differentials.

00:01:38.290 --> 00:01:43.090
So, in general, when we use the
method of differentials to

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:45.590
compute a linear approximation,
what we have is

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:53.720
that if y equals f of x, so if y
is given as a function of x,

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:59.640
then we have that so if we want
to change x a little bit

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:03.920
and figure out what the change
in y is, we have this formula,

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:08.080
which is that f of x plus dx--

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:11.350
so the function value
at a nearby point--

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:17.220
is approximately equal
to y plus dy.

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:20.790
So this is our formula for
linear approximation in terms

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:22.420
of differentials.

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:26.690
So in our case we have that our,
that the point we want is

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:30.360
x equals 2 and y equals 4.

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.340
And so we have, we know was dx
is also, because we want the

00:02:34.340 --> 00:02:36.580
approximation at the point 3.

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:41.530
So we want dx to be equal to
1 for this approximation.

00:02:41.530 --> 00:02:44.760
And so the question is, what
is dy going to be?

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:46.790
So that's the value
that we're after.

00:02:46.790 --> 00:02:49.060
That tells us how much the
function value changes.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:52.850
So to compute dy,
well dy is the

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:56.370
differential of the function.

00:02:56.370 --> 00:03:01.070
So this is d of the
square root of 10x

00:03:01.070 --> 00:03:02.320
minus x squared, quantity.

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.670
OK, so to compute this
differential now, we just use

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:09.620
our straight-forward rules
for doing this.

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:12.600
So we take a derivative
and then we

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:14.110
have dx's where necessary.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:17.760
So this is d of square root
of 10x minus x squared.

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:20.430
So the outermost function is
the square root function.

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:29.160
So this is going to be 1/2 times
10x minus x squared to

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:30.370
the minus 1/2.

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:34.280
So that's 1 over the square root
of 10x minus x squared.

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:37.840
And now I need to multiply by
the derivative of the inside

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:44.810
function, which is
10 minus 2x dx.

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:49.230
So really it's 10dx minus 2xdx
but I just, you know, pulled

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:50.640
that dx out in front.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:54.220
So we have a differential
equal to a differential.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:57.090
OK, and so, but we want this
value at this particular point

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:57.840
in question.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:01.250
So at this particular point in
question we have x equals 2

00:04:01.250 --> 00:04:02.690
and dx is equal to 1.

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:10.410
So the value of dy that we want
is equal to 1/2 times--

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:15.170
well this is again, OK, 10
times 2 minus 2 squared.

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:21.220
That's 16 to the minus
1/2 times--

00:04:21.220 --> 00:04:22.720
so here x equals 2.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.410
10 minus 4 is 6.

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:30.900
Times dx is just this 1 that
we're interested in.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:37.070
OK so 16 to the minus 1/2, 16 to
the 1/2 is 4, so 16 to the

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:38.900
minus 1/2 is 1/4.

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:43.070
So this is 1/2 times
1/4 times 6.

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:49.630
So that's 6/8, which is 3/4.

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:52.280
So our dy is 3/4.

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:55.970
So that means our linear
approximation that we're after

00:04:55.970 --> 00:05:04.100
is just f of 3, f of x plus dx
is approximately equal to our

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:08.360
value y that we, at our original
point, which was 4

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:10.030
plus the dy.

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:12.240
So plus 3/4.

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.220
So the linear approximation that
we get from this method

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:18.160
of differentials is exactly the
same approximation that we

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:19.940
would get if we did this
the other way.

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:22.770
But I think it's kind of
nice to do it in this

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:23.570
differential form.

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:27.170
Somehow it seems a little more
straightforward sometimes.

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:29.030
And OK, andso the answer
that we get out of

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:32.280
it is 4 plus 3/4.

00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:34.400
All right, so that's that.